===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|wir|lang=enm}}, {{term|wyr|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|wīr||wire, metal thread, wire-ornament}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*wīraz||wire}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*weyro-||a twist, thread, cord, wire}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*wey-||to turn, twist, weave, plait}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|Wir||wire|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Wiere||wire, metallic thread|lang=de}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|vír||wire|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|vira||to twist|lang=sv}}, Latin {{term/t|la|vieō||weave together}}, Welsh [[gwyr]] ('bent'), and Greek [[ίρις]] ('rainbow').

